    {
      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Investigate and fix missing 'annunci' link extraction in routes.ts\n**Description**: The crawler fails to find links on target pages due to a type cast bug (Attr.value returning undefined) and an unfiltered XPath. This plan adds debugging, fixes XPath filtering, corrects the type cast, improves scroll strategy, adds retry logic, and validates the fix on real pages.\n## All Steps\n1. **Debug link extraction: add logs and check real elements**: ## Goal\nIdentify why the crawler finds zero links containing 'annunci' on the target page, even though manual inspection shows them.\n\n## Task Type\nDebugging & Investigation — add temporary instrumentation to `src/routes.ts` to capture actual page state and DOM elements at runtime.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\nThe default handler in `src/routes.ts` (lines ~55-70) currently:\n1. Scrolls the page to `min(totalHeight * 0.3, 800)` (line 56).\n2. Waits 2 seconds (line 57).\n3. Uses `page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(...)` to extract href values (line 63).\n4. Casts each element to `Attr` and accesses `.value` (line 63) — this returns `undefined` for all `<a>` elements.\n5. Logs `Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \"annunci\"` even though no filtering is applied (line 67).\n6. Filters `hrefs` with `.filter(h => h?.toLowerCase().includes('annunci'))` (line 68) — but all hrefs are `undefined`, so the result is always empty.\n\nThe target page is provided via `request.url` from input `startUrls[]`.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/routes.ts` and locate the default request handler (around line 50-80).\n2. Add the following temporary instrumentation **after** the existing scroll and wait (after line 57):\n   - `console.log('🔍 Page URL:', request.url);`\n   - `console.log('📐 Scroll position:', await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollY));`\n   - `console.log('📏 Page height:', await page.evaluate(() => document.body.scrollHeight));`\n   - Take a full-page screenshot and save it to `screenshots/debug-fullpage.png` using `await page.screenshot({ path: 'screenshots/debug-fullpage.png', fullPage: true });` (create the directory if needed).\n3. Replace the existing link extraction block (lines 63-69) with a debug version that:\n   - Evaluates all `<a>` elements and returns an array of objects: `{ href: el.getAttribute('href'), text: el.textContent?.trim() }`.\n   - Logs the total number of `<a>` elements found, and the number of those whose href or text contains `'annunci'` (case-insensitive).\n   - Logs the first 10 such annunci-like elements with both href and text.\n4. Keep the dataset push unchanged (url + title).\n5. **Do not fix the underlying bugs yet** — only add diagnostic output.\n6. Run the crawler locally with the target URL(s) from the input and observe the terminal output and screenshot.\n\n## Reasoning\nThis step isolates the root cause by verifying: whether the page loads correctly, whether `<a>` elements exist, whether the scroll reaches the region containing annunci, whether `getAttribute('href')` returns values vs. the current buggy `Attr.value`, and why the filter produces zero results. The screenshot provides visual confirmation.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- Use `page.evaluate()` or `page.locator().evaluateAll()` consistently. For the debug extraction, call:\n```typescript\nconst allLinks = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map(el => ({\n        href: el.getAttribute('href'),\n        text: el.textContent?.trim()\n    }))\n);\n```\n- Filter with:\n```typescript\nconst annunciLinks = allLinks.filter(l =>\n    (l.href && l.href.toLowerCase().includes('annunci')) ||\n    (l.text && l.text.toLowerCase().includes('annunci'))\n);\n```\n- Add a check: if `annunciLinks.length === 0`, log a warning and also print the full `allLinks` array (or first 30) to inspect the actual href values.\n- Ensure the screenshot path is writable (local run: `mkdir -p screenshots` before running).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `page.screenshot` fails (e.g., no permission), log a warning and continue.\n- If the page does not load because of the crawling context, the error will be caught by Crawlee's retry module. Ensure the log still appears before any crash.\n- If `getAttribute('href')` returns `null` (anchor without href), these should be included but filtered out later.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the crawler with `npx tsx src/main.ts` and provide an input JSON containing the target URL (e.g., `{ \"startUrls\": [\"https://example.com/annunci\"], \"maxRequestsPerCrawl\": 1 }`).\n- Check the logs: you should see the page URL, scroll position, page height, total `<a>` count, annunci link count, and the first few annunci links.\n- If annunci link count is still 0, examine the full list of `<a>` elements from the logs to see if they contain 'annunci' in href or text, and verify the screenshot shows annunci elements visually.\n- After verifying the logs, revert the debug changes later (the next step will fix the bugs).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- `src/routes.ts` — existing router file.\n- Input JSON with `startUrls` pointing to the target page with annunci links.\n- Local environment: Node 20+, npm dependencies installed, Camoufox binary fetched (see Dockerfile).\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not change the dataset output schema (url + title).\n- Do not modify any other files (main.ts, tests, etc.).\n- Keep the step focused on debugging only — do not implement the eventual fixes.\n- All new logging must use `console.log` for clarity (Apify log is okay but console.log works for local debug).\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\nTemporary screenshots and full link dump may be heavy on large pages. For debug runs with single URL this is acceptable. Remove the instrumentation after debugging.\n\n## Documentation Impact\nAfter this step, document the findings (e.g., in a comment or a brief summary) so the next developer understands why the zero-link issue occurred.\n2. **Fix XPath to filter links containing 'annunci'**: ## Goal\nModify the XPath in `src/routes.ts` to correctly select only links whose `href` attribute contains the substring \"annunci\", instead of selecting all links with any `href`.\n\n## Task Type\nCode fix in existing scraping logic.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/routes.ts`, line 63 (approximately) in the default handler.\n- **Current code**:\n  ```typescript\n  const hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n      (els) => els.map((el) => (el as unknown as Attr).value),\n  );\n  ```\n- The XPath `//a[@href]` selects **every** `<a>` element that has an `href` attribute, regardless of its value. The subsequent log statement (line 67) incorrectly claims \"Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \\\"annunci\\\"\", but no filtering on \"annunci\" is actually performed.\n- The type cast `(el as unknown as Attr).value` is a separate bug (being fixed in step `fix-type-cast-getattribute`), but the XPath filter must be corrected **now** to ensure the right links are selected once the cast is fixed.\n\n## Action\nModify the XPath in the `page.locator` call to include a predicate that filters for `href` containing the string \"annunci\". Additionally, update the log message to accurately reflect the filtering done.\n\n## Reasoning\nThe current XPath selects all `href`-bearing links, which dilutes the extraction to potentially hundreds of irrelevant links (e.g., navigation, footer). The target use case requires links that point to \"annunci\" (listings/advertisements). By narrowing the XPath, we reduce noise and ensure that only relevant links are considered for further processing. This is the first step in the core extraction fixes; after the type cast bug is resolved, the filtered links will be correctly extracted.\n\n## Implementation Details\n1. Open `src/routes.ts` and locate the line with `'xpath=//a[@href]'` (around line 63).\n2. Change the XPath to: `'xpath=//a[contains(@href, \"annunci\")]'`\n3. Update the log message (likely on the same or next line) from:\n   `context.log.info(`Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \"annunci\"`);`\n   to:\n   `context.log.info(`Found ${hrefs.length} links with href containing \"annunci\"`);`\n4. Keep the existing `evaluateAll` callback as-is (the type cast bug will be fixed separately).\n\n**Important**: Do not change the callback logic (e.g., `.getAttribute('href')`) here – that belongs to the next step.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If the page contains no links with \"annunci\" in the href, `hrefs` will be an empty array. The log will correctly report 0 links. This is acceptable behavior.\n- If the page structure uses text content or different attribute names (e.g., `data-href`), the XPath filter may miss them. However, the step is specifically about filtering by `href` containing \"annunci\". Future enhancements (like retry with progressive scroll) may address lazy-loaded links.\n- The XPath is case-sensitive. If the target site uses uppercase or mixed-case \"Annunci\", the filter will not match. To account for that, consider using `translate()` or a case-insensitive XPath, but the initial fix should assume lowercase as per the user's context. This can be adjusted later if needed.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the crawler locally against a page known to contain links with \"annunci\" in their href. Example: `npx tsx src/main.ts` with appropriate start URL.\n- Check the log output: it should show a count that is less than or equal to the total number of links on the page.\n- Verify that the extracted `hrefs` array (when the type cast is later fixed) contains only those links whose href includes \"annunci\". For now, the array will still be `undefined` due to the cast bug – that's expected and will be resolved in the next step.\n- If unit or integration tests exist for the route, adjust them to expect the filtered count (or skip them temporarily until the cast fix is merged).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends on `debug-current-extraction`, which should have confirmed that the unfiltered XPath extracts many irrelevant links and that the log message is misleading. No other code changes are required before this step.\n- The step `fix-type-cast-getattribute` will follow and fix the `.value` bug to make the extracted hrefs meaningful.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify any other files or add new dependencies.\n- Maintain ESM imports and `.js` extensions if re-exporting.\n- Follow project code conventions (4-space indent, single quotes, Prettier formatting).\n- The change must not introduce TypeScript or lint errors.\n- After the change, the log statement must be truthful about the filtering.\n3. **Fix Attr.value cast to getAttribute('href')**: ## Goal\nReplace the erroneous type cast `(el as unknown as Attr).value` with a correct call to `el.getAttribute('href')` in `src/routes.ts`. This bug causes `undefined` values to be returned for every link, making the crawler believe no links were found even on pages that contain many anchor tags.\n\n## Task Type\nCode correction – bugfix with type safety improvement.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/routes.ts`\n- **Lines 63-67**: The default route handler extracts links via `page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(...)`.\n- Current code:\n  ```typescript\n  const hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n      (els) => els.map((el) => (el as unknown as Attr).value),\n  );\n  ```\n- `evaluateAll` passes **DOM elements** (`HTMLAnchorElement`) to the callback, not `Attr` nodes. `Attr.value` is a property of `Attr` objects (e.g., from `document.createAttribute`). `HTMLAnchorElement` does not have a `.value` property, so the cast yields `undefined` for every element.\n- The logged message at line ~67 says `Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \"annunci\"`, but `hrefs` is an array of `undefined` values; the length equals the number of links on the page, leading to a false positive. The actual href values are lost.\n- The XPath filter for `\"annunci\"` will be addressed in a separate step (`fix-xpath-filter-annunci`). This step focuses solely on the type cast.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/routes.ts`.\n2. Locate the `evaluateAll` call (around line 63).\n3. Replace the callback body:\n   - **Before**: `(els) => els.map((el) => (el as unknown as Attr).value)`\n   - **After**: `(els) => els.map((el) => el.getAttribute('href'))`\n4. Update the log message (line ~67) to reflect the actual content (remove or adjust the misleading phrase `\"links containing \\\"annunci\\\"\"`; for now use `\"links found on page\"`; the true filtering will be added later).\n5. Ensure the code compiles with TypeScript strict mode – `getAttribute` returns `string | null`; since the XPath `//a[@href]` guarantees `href` exists, the result will always be a string. No additional null filtering is strictly required, but you may add a filter for non-null values to be safe (optional).\n\n## Reasoning\nThe root cause of the “no links found” behavior: every extracted value is `undefined`, so downstream logic (e.g., filtering, counting) sees an array of `undefined` and may subsequently discard or ignore them. Real href strings can only be obtained by calling `el.getAttribute('href')` on the DOM element. This fix directly resolves the data loss.\n\n## Implementation Details\nExact code change:\n\n```typescript\n// BEFORE (buggy):\nconst hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map((el) => (el as unknown as Attr).value),\n);\n\n// AFTER (fixed):\nconst hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map((el) => el.getAttribute('href')),\n);\n```\n\nUpdate the log line (near 67) to something accurate:\n\n```typescript\nlog.info(`Found ${hrefs.length} links on the page`);\n```\n\n(Optionally filter out null values:\n```typescript\nconst hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map((el) => el.getAttribute('href')).filter(Boolean),\n);\n```\nBut this should not be necessary given the XPath constraint. Add only if downstream code expects non-null strings.)\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If a page has no elements matching `//a[@href]`, `evaluateAll` returns an empty array; the fix works correctly.\n- The XPath already ensures the attribute exists, so `getAttribute('href')` will not return `null`. If you add `.filter(Boolean)`, it safely excludes any unexpected `null` or `undefined`.\n- The internal `evaluateAll` runs in the browser context; the fix does not change the execution context or risk type errors.\n\n## Validation\n1. Run the existing test suite: `npm test` (Vitest). The integration test at `test/main.test.ts` crawls `https://apify.com` and expects `requestsFinished >= 10` and items with `url` and `title`. After the fix, links should be correctly extracted, so the test should still pass (the test does not check link count, but the overall crawling flow remains intact).\n2. Optionally, run a manual test with a target page known to have links (e.g., any list page) and verify that `hrefs` now contains actual URLs instead of `undefined`. Add a temporary `console.log(hrefs)` inside the handler to inspect.\n3. Confirm TypeScript compilation: `npx tsc --noEmit` yields no errors.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- **Prior step**: `debug-current-extraction` should have been completed, confirming the `undefined` values via logging or debugging.\n- **Input**: The existing `src/routes.ts` file with the buggy code.\n- **No external API changes** are required.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify other parts of the route handler (e.g., the XPath filter, scroll logic) – those are addressed in separate steps.\n- Keep the code style consistent with the project rules: TypeScript strict, ESM imports with `.js` extension, `apify/log`, single quotes, 4-space indent, Prettier formatting.\n- The fix must be contained to the `evaluateAll` callback and the log message. No new dependencies or imports.\n4. **Enhance scroll depth to trigger lazy-loaded annunci**: ## Goal\n\nModify the scroll logic in `src/routes.ts` to scroll deeper and progressively, ensuring lazy-loaded dynamic content (e.g., 'annunci' links) is fully loaded before extraction.\n\n## Task Type\n\nCode modification (enhancement) – update the scroll behavior in the default handler of the Playwright router.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n\nIn `src/routes.ts` (around line 56), the current scroll implementation uses:\n```typescript\nconst totalHeight = await page.evaluate(() => document.body.scrollHeight);\nconst scrollTo = Math.min(totalHeight * 0.3, 800);\nawait page.evaluate((y) => window.scrollTo(0, y), scrollTo);\n```\nThis caps scroll depth at 800px, which is insufficient for pages that lazy-load content (like 'annunci' listings) beyond that point. The page is visited via Camoufox browser, and the extraction step (to be fixed in earlier steps) relies on the DOM being fully populated.\n\n## Action\n\nReplace the single-scroll logic with a progressive multi-step scroll that moves down the page in steps, waiting between scrolls for dynamic content to render.\n\n## Reasoning\n\nA fixed 800px cap misses content below that depth. By scrolling in increments (e.g., viewport height * 0.8 or 600px) with a short delay, we trigger lazy-loading events and ensure the entire page content, especially 'annunci' sections, becomes available for extraction.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n1. Locate the scroll block in `src/routes.ts` (currently lines 56-58).\n2. Replace with a loop:\n   - Starting Y = 0.\n   - Set `scrollStep = 600` (adjustable) and `maxScrolls = 20`.\n   - For `i` from 0 to maxScrolls:\n     - `await page.evaluate((y) => window.scrollBy(0, y), scrollStep);`\n     - `await page.waitForTimeout(500);`\n     - Get current `scrollY` and `scrollHeight` via `page.evaluate`.\n     - If `scrollY + window.innerHeight >= scrollHeight`, break (bottom reached).\n     - If content height hasn't increased after 3 consecutive scrolls (optional), break to avoid infinite loops.\n3. Keep a fallback: if the page fails to provide body.scrollHeight, log a warning and use the original single scroll (capped at 800px).\n4. Add logging with `log.info` to report scroll count and final scrollY.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n\n- `page.evaluate` may fail if the page is closed or navigated away; wrap in try-catch and fall back.\n- Very short pages: break early when `scrollY + window.innerHeight >= scrollHeight`.\n- Pages with infinite scroll: use `maxScrolls` limit (default 20) to avoid infinite loops.\n- Ensure `page.waitForTimeout` is used (Playwright 1.60.0 supports it).\n\n## Validation\n\n1. Run the crawler locally with a test URL known to have lazy-loaded 'annunci' content (e.g., the target used in the investigation).\n2. Before change: log shows few or no 'annunci' links found.\n3. After change: log shows more links, and final scroll position > 800px.\n4. Push dataset items with url+title; confirm they include the annunci entries.\n5. Ensure no regression on simple pages (e.g., apify.com).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n\n- This step depends on `debug-current-extraction` being completed (to have baseline metrics).\n- It does **not** depend on the XPath or type-cast fixes (those are separate).\n- It affects the default route handler in `src/routes.ts`.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Only modify the scroll block; do not touch extraction, XPath, or type-cast logic in this step.\n- Use Camoufox browser (Playwright environment).\n- Keep the scroll delay reasonable (500ms) to avoid excessive crawl time.\n- The change must be compatible with the existing `Actor.pushData` and logging pattern.\n- No new dependencies beyond Playwright APIs.\n5. **Add retry with progressive scroll for missing links**: ## Goal\nAdd retry logic with progressive scrolling in `src/routes.ts` so that if no 'annunci' links are found after the initial scroll attempt, the crawler will scroll further in increments and re-extract until links appear or a max depth is reached.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification – add retry loop after initial extraction in the default route handler.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- File: `src/routes.ts` (the default request handler inside `createPlaywrightRouter`).\n- Current extraction logic (after bug fixes): uses `page.locator('xpath=//a[contains(@href, \"annunci\")]')` then `el.getAttribute('href')`.\n- Current scroll: a single `page.evaluate` that scrolls to `Math.min(totalHeight * 0.3, 800)` pixels. This may be insufficient for pages with lazy-loaded content far below the fold.\n- The handler checks `if (hrefs.length === 0)` and logs a warning, but does not retry.\n- The handler runs on every request; it can be extended with a loop.\n\n## Action\n1. Locate the extraction block in `src/routes.ts` (after the line that logs `Navigating to ${request.url}` and before `await Actor.pushData`).  \n2. Wrap the scroll+extract sequence in a retry loop.  \n   - Initial scroll remains the same.  \n   - After extraction, if `hrefs.length === 0` and a maximum retry count (e.g., 5) is not yet reached, scroll down by an additional increment (e.g., 500px) and wait for a short delay (e.g., 1.5 seconds) for lazy-load to trigger.  \n   - Re‑evaluate the XPath to extract links.  \n   - Break the loop once links are found or max retries exceeded.  \n3. Log the number of retries performed and the final link count.  \n4. Ensure the retry loop does not block the dataset push: if links are still empty after all retries, continue without pushing an empty array (or push a placeholder as before).  \n\n## Reasoning\nLazy‑loaded content (especially in infinite-scroll or paginated sections) may not be visible after a single small scroll. Progressive scrolling with retry mimics user behavior and increases reliability. The retry limit prevents infinite loops on pages that genuinely have no matching links.\n\n## Implementation Details\n```typescript\n// Inside default handler, after page.goto and initial wait\nconst maxRetries = 5;\nlet hrefs: (string | null)[] = [];\nfor (let attempt = 0; attempt < maxRetries; attempt++) {\n  // Scroll on first attempt; subsequent attempts scroll further\n  await page.evaluate((scrollOffset) => {\n    window.scrollBy(0, scrollOffset);\n  }, attempt === 0 ? Math.min(await page.evaluate(() => document.body.scrollHeight) * 0.3, 800) : 500);\n  // Wait for potential dynamically loaded content\n  await page.waitForTimeout(1500);\n  // Extract links (using the corrected XPath and getAttribute)\n  hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[contains(@href, \"annunci\")]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map((el) => el.getAttribute('href'))\n  );\n  if (hrefs.length > 0) {\n    break;\n  }\n  log.info(`Attempt ${attempt + 1}: no annunci links found, retrying...`);\n}\n```\n- Keep the existing logging for `hrefs.length`.\n- Update the comment to explain the retry loop.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `page.evaluate` throws due to page closing, catch and break the loop.\n- If the page has no scrollable content (scrollHeight <= 0), skip further scrolling.\n- If `maxRetries` is reached and still no links, log a final warning and proceed with empty array (no link push).\n- Ensure `page.waitForTimeout` is not using a global import; it's available on the page object.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the crawler locally on a page that contains 'annunci' links loaded via lazy‑loading (e.g., a classifieds listing).  \n- Assert that the output dataset contains the expected annunci links.  \n- Run the existing Vitest integration test (`test/main.test.ts`) to ensure no regressions.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends on the previous fixes in `src/routes.ts`: XPath filter, `getAttribute` correction, and scroll strategy improvement (already assumed in the plan).  \n- No new dependencies required; uses Playwright’s built-in methods.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify the overall request flow (still uses `router` and `Actor.pushData`).  \n- Keep the change in the same file (`src/routes.ts`) and same handler.  \n- Avoid introducing `any` types; use `string | null` for hrefs.\n6. **Update tests and validate fix on real target pages**: ## Goal\nValidate that the applied fixes (XPath filter, getAttribute('href'), enhanced scroll, retry) correctly extract links containing 'annunci' from real target pages. Ensure existing tests still pass.\n\n## Task Type\nTesting & Validation — write and run Vitest integration tests using the actual PlaywrightCrawler with Camoufox browser against real URLs.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\nThe previous steps modified `src/routes.ts`:\n- Changed XPath from `//a[@href]` to `//a[contains(@href, \"annunci\")]` (or added JS filter after extraction).\n- Replaced `(el as unknown as Attr).value` with `el.getAttribute('href')`.\n- Enhanced scroll strategy (increased max scroll or progressive scrolling).\n- Added retry logic when no links are found (scroll further and re-extract).\n\nExisting test at `test/main.test.ts` crawls `https://apify.com` and asserts `requestsFinished >= 10` and that each dataset item has `url` and `title`. This test must continue to pass.\n\nInput schema expects `startUrls[]` and `maxRequestsPerCrawl`. The test can override these by directly calling `Actor.main` or creating a custom `PlaywrightCrawler` instance. Data is pushed to the default dataset via `Actor.pushData`.\n\n## Action\n1. Create a new Vitest test file `test/annunci.test.ts` (or extend `main.test.ts` with a second test).\n2. In the new test:\n   - Use a real URL known to contain multiple 'annunci' links (e.g., `https://www.subito.it/annunci-immobiliari/vendita/milano/` or the page the user reported).\n   - Configure a `PlaywrightCrawler` with the same `launchOptions` as in `src/main.ts` (Camoufox).\n   - Set `maxRequestsPerCrawl` to 1, `initialCookies` if needed, enable `useSessionPool: false` for simplicity.\n   - Add request handler (the same `router` from routes.ts) or use the existing one.\n   - After crawling, retrieve dataset items via `Actor.getDataset().getData()`.\n   - **Assert** that at least one item has a `url` property containing `'annunci'` (case-insensitive).\n   - **Assert** that the debug log (captured via `apify.log` spy) shows a message like `\"Found N links containing 'annunci'\"` with N > 0.\n   - **Assert** that the extracted links are valid absolute URLs (starting with http or https).\n3. Run the existing test (`test/main.test.ts`) to confirm no regression: `npx vitest run test/main.test.ts`.\n4. Run both tests: `npm test` (or `npx vitest run`). Ensure all pass.\n5. Optionally, add a unit test for the link extraction function if it was extracted to a helper (`src/utils/linkExtractor.ts`).\n\n## Reasoning\nWithout validation, we cannot confirm the fixes work on the exact scenario the user reported. The integration test replicates the user's failure case and proves that links are now correctly found. Using a real website ensures that lazy‑loading, dynamic content, and anti‑bot protections are handled.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- **Test file**: `test/annunci.test.ts`\n- **Structure**:\n  ```ts\n  import { Actor } from 'apify';\n  import { PlaywrightCrawler } from '@crawlee/playwright';\n  import { router } from '../src/routes.js';\n  import { test, expect } from 'vitest';\n  \n  test('crawls a page and finds annunci links', async () => {\n      const testUrl = 'https://www.subito.it/annunci-immobiliari/vendita/milano/';\n      const crawler = new PlaywrightCrawler({\n          requestHandler: router,\n          launchContext: {\n              launcher: /** use camoufox launcher */\n          },\n          maxRequestsPerCrawl: 1,\n      });\n      await crawler.run([testUrl]);\n      const dataset = await Actor.openDataset();\n      const { items } = await dataset.getData();\n      expect(items.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);\n      const annunciLinks = items.filter(item => (item.url as string).toLowerCase().includes('annunci'));\n      expect(annunciLinks.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);\n  }, 60000); // timeout 60s\n  ```\n- Ensure `launcher` is imported from `camoufox-js` or use the same configuration as `src/main.ts`.\n- To capture logs, use `vi.spyOn(apifyLog, 'info')` or similar; but for simplicity, rely on dataset items.\n- The test may need `--experimental-vm-modules` if using ESM; the project already uses `tsx` so it should work.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If the target page is temporarily unreachable, the test should fail with a clear message. Use `test.setTimeout` to allow network delays (60s).\n- If the page has no links with 'annunci' (e.g., empty results), the test will correctly fail – this indicates the page selection might be wrong. Use a URL the user confirmed has annunci.\n- Ensure the test does not depend on local state (e.g., dataset state from previous runs). Use `Actor.pushData` as the real actor does.\n- If the browser fails to launch, the test will time out; include a `beforeEach`/`afterEach` to handle cleanup.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npx vitest run test/annunci.test.ts` – expected: tests pass.\n- Run `npx vitest run test/main.test.ts` – expected: tests pass.\n- Run `npm test` (which runs all tests) – expected: all green.\n- Manually inspect dataset output from the test (printed or logged) to confirm links contain 'annunci'.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- Depends on previous step outputs: modified `src/routes.ts` with fixed XPath, getAttribute, scroll, retry logic.\n- Depends on existing `src/main.ts` for crawler configuration (can be reused).\n- Input: the real URL to test (hardcoded in test, as agreed with user).\n- Environment: same as Docker/local – Node 20+, ESM, Vitest, Camoufox browser binary available.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify `src/routes.ts` or `src/main.ts` in this step – only tests.\n- Keep tests self‑contained; do not read from the same dataset as production runs.\n- Use the same `apify` SDK version (^3.7.0).\n- Follow the existing test pattern (usage of `Actor.main` or direct crawler instantiation).",
